# Fleet Authority Governance & Command Hierarchy

**Canonical source:** `Universe/Fleet/fleet_authority_governance_and_command_hierarchy.md`

Reference before political, command, intelligence escalation, or authority-conflict scenes. Hard governance model — not narrative content.

**Also load:** `Universe/Fleet/fleet_communication_sensor_and_information_warfare_doctrine.md`

## Core principle

Fleet Authority = **layered governance**, not single centralized command. Political, military, and operational authority are separated — and frequently conflict in crisis.

## Three parallel systems

| Layer | Role | Weakness |
|-------|------|----------|
| **A. Civilian political** | Governance, trade, diplomacy, funding | Slow; no real-time military response |
| **B. Military command** | Deployments, strategy, doctrine | Dependent on comms/information integrity |
| **C. Field command (ship)** | Tactical decisions, survival, engagement | Overrides delayed/contradictory higher orders |

## Chain of command

**Normal:** Civilian → Military → Task Forces → Captains

**Combat/degraded comms:** Captains may override delayed, contradictory, or ambiguous orders. **Field survival supersedes hierarchical delay.**

## Information authority (critical)

Command valid only if: current · consistent with local sensors · not contradicted by independent systems. Otherwise → **authority defaults to local ship command**.

## Command fragmentation (Fleet-scale conflict)

Political authority becomes symbolic; military command partially blind; field command becomes primary. Produces multiple "truth states" and conflicting legitimate orders.

## Maris Chen

Fleet Intelligence Bureau — **civil-military interface**. No enforcement authority; reports need transmission + approval. Lost/delayed reports can vanish without systemic awareness.

## Kestrel Veil

**Field command level only.** No fleet strategy or political influence. Resilient in fragmented command via local interpretation and survival decisions.

## Narrative rule

Reflect delay, competing valid orders, partial strategic visibility. No authority layer is omniscient.

## Consistency lock

Overrides all previous implied governance structures.
